6 ARTICLE 10
7 PRUDENTIAL STANDARDS
8 Sec. 65. (1) A licensee shall maintain at all times a tangible
9 net worth of the greater of $100,000.00 or 3% of total assets for
10 the first $100,000,000.00, 2% of additional assets for
11 $100,000,000.00 to $1,000,000,000.00, and 0.5% of additional assets
12 for over $1,000,000,000.00.
13 (2) Tangible net worth must be demonstrated at initial
14 application by the applicant's most recent audited or unaudited
15 financial statements in accordance with section 25(2)(f).
16 (3) Notwithstanding the foregoing provisions of this section,
17 the director has the authority, for good cause shown, to exempt, in
18 part or in whole, from the requirements of this section any
19 applicant or licensee.
20 Sec. 67. (1) An applicant for a money transmission license
21 must provide, and a licensee at all times shall maintain, security
22 consisting of a surety bond in a form satisfactory to the director
23 or, with the director's approval, a deposit instead of a bond in
24 accordance with this section.
25 (2) The amount of the required security is either of the
26 following:
27 (a) The greater of $100,000.00 or an amount equal to 100% of
28 the licensee's average daily money transmission liability in this
29 state calculated for the most recently completed 3-month period, up
WAM H02309'25 (H-2) tvg6xh

44
1 to a maximum of $500,000.00.
2 (b) In the event that the licensee's tangible net worth
3 exceeds 10% of total assets, the licensee shall maintain a surety
4 bond of $100,000.00.
5 (3) A licensee that maintains a bond in the maximum amount
6 provided for in subsection (2)(a) or (b), as applicable, shall not
7 be required to calculate its average daily money transmission
8 liability in this state for purposes of this section.
9 (4) A licensee may exceed the maximum required bond amount
10 under section 71(1)(d).
11 Sec. 69. (1) A licensee shall maintain at all times
12 permissible investments that have a market value computed in
13 accordance with United States generally accepted accounting
14 principles of not less than the aggregate amount of all of its
15 outstanding money transmission obligations.
16 (2) Except for permissible investments enumerated in section
17 71(1), the director, with respect to any licensee, may by rule or
18 order limit the extent to which a specific investment maintained by
19 a licensee within a class of permissible investments may be
20 considered a permissible investment, if the specific investment
21 represents undue risk to customers, not reflected in the market
22 value of investments.
23 (3) Permissible investments, even if commingled with other
24 assets of the licensee, are held in trust for the benefit of the
25 purchasers and holders of the licensee's outstanding money
26 transmission obligations in the event of insolvency, the filing of
27 a petition by or against the licensee under 11 USC 101 to 110, for
28 bankruptcy or reorganization, the filing of a petition by or
29 against the licensee for receivership, the commencement of any
