8 ARTICLE 11
9 ENFORCEMENT
10 Sec. 73. (1) The director may suspend or revoke a license or
11 order a licensee to revoke the designation of an authorized
12 delegate under any of the following circumstances:
13 (a) The licensee violates this act, a rule promulgated under
14 this act, an order or declaratory ruling issued under this act, or
15 any applicable state or federal law.
16 (b) The licensee does not cooperate with an examination or
17 investigation by the director.
18 (c) The licensee engages in fraud, intentional
19 misrepresentation, or gross negligence.
20 (d) An authorized delegate is convicted of a violation of a
21 state or federal anti-money laundering statute, or violates a rule
22 adopted or an order issued under this act, as a result of the
23 licensee's willful misconduct or willful blindness, as that term is
24 defined in section 4701 of the revised judicature act of 1961, 1961
25 PA 236, MCL 600.4701.
26 (e) The competence, experience, character, or general fitness
27 of the licensee, authorized delegate, person in control of a
28 licensee, key individual, or responsible person of the authorized
29 delegate indicates that it is not in the public interest to permit
WAM H02309'25 (H-2) tvg6xh

52
1 the person to provide money transmission.
2 (f) Subject to subsection (2), the licensee engages in an
3 unsafe or unsound practice.
4 (g) The licensee fails to maintain the minimum net worth
5 required under section 65 or is insolvent, suspends payment of its
6 obligations, or makes a general assignment for the benefit of its
7 creditors.
8 (h) The licensee does not remove an authorized delegate after
9 the director issues and serves on the licensee a final order
10 including a finding that the authorized delegate has violated this
11 act.
12 (2) In determining whether a licensee is engaging in an unsafe
13 or unsound practice, the director may consider the size and
14 condition of the licensee's money transmission, the magnitude of
15 the loss, the gravity of the violation of this act, and the
16 previous conduct of the person involved.
17 Sec. 75. (1) If in the opinion of the director a licensee or
18 an authorized delegate is, has, or is about to engage in a practice
19 that poses a threat of financial loss or threat to the public
20 welfare or is, has, or is about to violate a law, rule, or order,
21 the director may issue and serve on the licensee or authorized
22 delegate a cease and desist order under this section.
23 (2) A cease and desist order issued under this section must
24 contain a statement of the facts constituting the alleged practice
25 or violation. A person ordered to cease and desist must be entitled
26 to a hearing before the commissioner if a written request for a
27 hearing is filed with the commissioner not more than 30 days after
28 the effective date of the order. A hearing must be conducted in
29 accordance with the provisions of the administrative procedures act
WAM H02309'25 (H-2) tvg6xh

53
1 of 1969, 1969 PA 306, MCL 24.201 to 24.328.
2 (3) A licensee or authorized delegate ordered to cease and
3 desist may consent to issuance of a cease and desist order under
4 this section. A licensee or authorized delegate ordered to cease
5 and desist also consents to the issuance of the cease and desist
6 order if the licensee or a duly authorized representative of the
7 licensee fails to appear at a hearing described in subsection (2).
8 (4) If a licensee or authorized delegate consents under
9 subsection (3), or if the director finds based on the record made
10 at the hearing that the practice or violation specified in the
11 order is established, the cease and desist order becomes final. The
12 order may require the licensee or authorized delegate and its
13 officers, directors, members, partners, trustees, employees,
14 agents, or control persons to cease and desist from the practice or
15 violation and to take affirmative action to correct the conditions
16 resulting from the practice or violation.
17 (5) Except as provided in subsection (6) or to the extent it
18 is stayed, modified, terminated, or set aside by the director or a
19 court, a cease and desist order is effective on the date of
20 service.
21 (6) A cease and desist order issued with a licensee's or
22 authorized delegate's consent is effective at the time specified in
23 the order and remains effective and enforceable as provided in the
24 order.
