1 MISCELLANEOUS PROVISIONS
2 Sec. 85. In applying and construing this act, consideration
3 must be given to the need to promote uniformity of the law with
4 respect to its subject matter among states that enact it.
5 Sec. 87. If any provision of this act or its application to
6 any person or circumstance is held invalid, the invalidity does not
7 affect other provisions or applications of this act which can be
8 given effect without the invalid provision or application, and to
9 this end the provisions of this act are severable.
10 Sec. 89. (1) A person licensed in this state to engage in the
11 business of money transmission shall not be subject to the
12 provisions of this act, to the extent that the provisions conflict
13 with current law or establish new requirements not imposed under
14 current law, until July 1, 2027.
15 (2) Notwithstanding subsection (1), a licensee shall only be
16 required to amend its authorized delegate contracts for contracts
17 entered into or amended after January 1, 2027 or the completion of
18 any transition period contemplated under subsection (1). Nothing
19 herein shall be construed as limiting an authorized delegate's
20 obligations to operate in full compliance with this act as required
21 by section 51(2).
22 (3) A person providing payroll processing services in this
23 state without a license shall not be considered in violation of
24 section 21 if the person applies for a license before July 1, 2027.
25 The director may for good cause extend the transition period in
26 conjunction with the extension of an application period.
27 Enacting section 1. The money transmission services act, 2006
